title: Climate Indicators Helper Functions
text: package cames dataset examples seven different climate indicators. Let’s use maximum temperature indicator temp_max_data.

title: Climate Indicators Helper Functions
text: can compute climatological monthly normals summarise_normal() function. example, function summarise_normal() receive grouped data municipality id month, compute climatological monthly normal considering values 1961 1990.
code: library(dplyr) library(lubridate) library(climindi)  temp_max_normals <- temp_max_data |>   # Identify month   mutate(month = month(date)) |>   # Group by id variable, year and month   group_by(code_muni, month) |>   summarise_normal(date_var = date, value_var = value, year_start = 1961, year_end = 1990) |>   ungroup() temp_max_normals #> # A tibble: 48 × 5 #>    code_muni month normal_mean normal_p10 normal_p90 #>        <int> <dbl>       <dbl>      <dbl>      <dbl> #>  1   3106200     1        27.9       24.0       31.2 #>  2   3106200     2        28.5       25.5       30.9 #>  3   3106200     3        28.3       25.4       30.9 #>  4   3106200     4        27.2       24.6       29.6 #>  5   3106200     5        25.8       22.8       28.3 #>  6   3106200     6        24.7       21.9       27.3 #>  7   3106200     7        24.4       20.9       27.2 #>  8   3106200     8        26.1       22.2       29.8 #>  9   3106200     9        27.1       22.6       31.1 #> 10   3106200    10        27.5       23.0       31.5 #> # ℹ 38 more rows

title: Climate Indicators Helper Functions
text: summarize functions available package, possible compute several aggregated indicators, use normals computed . Thus, supply data using groups structures normals. function summarise_temp_max() computes total 19 indicators. Let’s plot one .
code: indi_temp_max <- temp_max_data |>  # Identify year  mutate(year = year(date)) |>  # Identify month  mutate(month = month(date)) |>  # Group by id variable, year and month  group_by(code_muni, year, month) |>  # Compute maximum temperature indicators  summarise_temp_max(value_var = value, normals_df = temp_max_normals) |>  # Ungroup  ungroup() indi_temp_max #> # A tibble: 3,024 × 24 #>    code_muni  year month count normal_mean normal_p10 normal_p90  mean median #>        <int> <dbl> <dbl> <int>       <dbl>      <dbl>      <dbl> <dbl>  <dbl> #>  1   3106200  1961     1    31        27.9       24.0       31.2  25.9   26.1 #>  2   3106200  1961     2    28        28.5       25.5       30.9  28.2   28.7 #>  3   3106200  1961     3    31        28.3       25.4       30.9  28.3   28.9 #>  4   3106200  1961     4    30        27.2       24.6       29.6  28.1   28.1 #>  5   3106200  1961     5    31        25.8       22.8       28.3  25.5   25.5 #>  6   3106200  1961     6    30        24.7       21.9       27.3  24.8   24.9 #>  7   3106200  1961     7    31        24.4       20.9       27.2  25.2   25.1 #>  8   3106200  1961     8    31        26.1       22.2       29.8  27.8   27.7 #>  9   3106200  1961     9    30        27.1       22.6       31.1  31.8   32.7 #> 10   3106200  1961    10    31        27.5       23.0       31.5  28.4   29.3 #> # ℹ 3,014 more rows #> # ℹ 15 more variables: sd <dbl>, se <dbl>, max <dbl>, min <dbl>, p10 <dbl>, #> #   p25 <dbl>, p75 <dbl>, p90 <dbl>, heat_waves_3d <int>, heat_waves_5d <int>, #> #   hot_days <int>, t_25 <int>, t_30 <int>, t_35 <int>, t_40 <int> library(ggplot2)  indi_temp_max |>   mutate(date = as.Date(paste0(year,"-",month,"-01"))) |>   ggplot(aes(x = date, y = p90)) +   geom_line(stat = "identity") +   geom_smooth() +   facet_wrap(~ code_muni) #> `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

title: Add waves — add_wave

title: Add waves — add_wave

title: Add waves — add_wave
text: .x data.frame object. normals_df data.frame object normal values, computed summarise_normal(). threshold numeric. positive negative threshold value added normal mean value. Use value zero consider normal value. threshold_cond string. threshold condition. Use gte "greather equal" lte less equal. size numeric. Minimum size sequence. var_name string. Variable name outputs result.

title: Add waves — add_wave
text: data.frame var_name variable logical values.

title: Add waves — add_wave
text: helper function detect sequence events ordered vector considering historical normal values. event considered sequence values certain size (size argument) greather less (threshold_cond argument) historical normal (normal argument) plus threshold (threshold value). function fill variable var_name TRUE record belongs event.

title: Compute precipitation indicators from grouped data — summarise_precipitation
text: rain spells indicators computed based climatological normals, created summarise_normal() function passed normals_df argument. Keys join normals data must present (like id, year, month)  use names. variables rs3 rs5 must present dataset. variables can computed add_wave() function. Plase follow function example correct arguments. following indicators computed group. count Count data points normal_mean Climatological normal mean, normals_df argument normal_p10 Climatological 10th percentile, normals_df argument normal_p90 Climatological 90th percentile, normals_df argument mean Average median Median sd Standard deviation se Standard error max Maximum value min Minimum value p10 10th percentile p25 25th percentile p75 75th percentile p90 90th percentile rs3 Count rain spells occurences, 3 consecutive days rain climatological normal average value rs5 Count rain spells occurences, 5 consecutive days rain climatological normal average value p_1 Count days precipitation 1mm p_5 Count days precipitation 5mm p_10 Count days precipitation 10mm p_50 Count days precipitation 50mm p_100 Count days precipitation 100mm d_3 Count sequences 3 days without precipitation d_5 Count sequences 5 days without precipitation d_10 Count sequences 10 days without precipitation d_15 Count sequences 15 days without precipitation d_20 Count sequences 20 days without precipitation d_25 Count sequences 25 days without precipitation

title: Compute precipitation indicators from grouped data — summarise_precipitation
